  "prompt": "Do questions on Quora that are non-anonymous get more distribution when posted as a follow-up to another question?",
  "response": "On Quora, the distribution of a post or question depends on several factors, including its relevance, quality, and engagement potential. While there isn't a definitive rule that posting a follow-up question guarantees more distribution, there are some considerations:\n\n1. **Context and Relevance**: Follow-up questions often build on existing discussions, making them more relevant to users who engaged with the original question. This can increase visibility and engagement, leading to better distribution.\n\n2. **Audience Familiarity**: Follow-up questions are more likely to be seen by users who already interacted with the original question, as they may be notified or recommended related content.\n\n3. **Quality Matters**: The distribution of a follow-up question still depends on its quality. If it adds value, sparks interest, or encourages thoughtful discussion, it's more likely to be promoted by Quora's algorithms.\n\n4. **Anonymity vs. Non-Anonymity**: Non-anonymous questions may receive slightly more engagement if the asker has a strong profile or following, but this is not always the case. The content of the question is usually more important than whether it's anonymous or not.\n\nIn summary, while follow-up questions can benefit from being part of an ongoing conversation, their distribution ultimately depends on their quality and relevance, not just their format or timing.",
